  <refentry id="dbp.man.dbp.initarchive">
    <indexterm><primary>dbp-initarchive</><secondary>Reference For</></>
    <refentryinfo>
      <address><email>jgoerzen@complete.org</email></address>
      <author><firstname>John</firstname><surname>Goerzen</surname></author>
    </refentryinfo>

    <refmeta>
      <refentrytitle>dbp-initarchive</refentrytitle>
      <manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
      <refmiscinfo>John Goerzen</refmiscinfo>
    </refmeta>

    <refnamediv>
      <refname>dbp-initarchive</refname>
      <refpurpose>Initialize an archive and tree for darcs-buildpackage</>
    </refnamediv>

    <refsynopsisdiv>
      <cmdsynopsis>
	<command>dbp-initarchive</command>
	<arg choice="plain"><replaceable>archive_name</replaceable></arg>
	<arg choice="plain"><replaceable>archive_location</></>
	<arg choice="plain"><replaceable>working_location</></>
      </cmdsynopsis>
    </refsynopsisdiv>

    <refsect1 id="dbp.man.dbp.initarchive.description">
      <title>Description</title>
      <para>
	&dbp-initarchive; is designed to set up both the &tla; archive
	and the working area for a &dbp; setup.  It automatically
	handles all the tasks relating to running tla and &dbp;
      </para>
      <para>
	&dbp-initarchive; will create the tla archive
	<property>archive_name</property> in
	<property>archive_location</property>, and check it out into
	<property>working_location</property>, having initialized that
	working area for &dbp;.  If
	<filename>~/.darcs-buildpackage</filename> does not exist, it
	will be created and the working location will be written into it.
      </para>
    </refsect1>

    <refsect1 id="dbp.man.dbp.initarchove.options">
      <title>Options</title>
      <variablelist>
	<varlistentry><term>archive_name</term>
	  <listitem><para>Gives the tla name of the archive to
	      create.  tla must not know anything about it prior to
	      running this command.  An example would be
	      foo@example.com--debian.</para>
	  </listitem>
	</varlistentry>

	<varlistentry><term>archive_location</term>
	  <listitem><para>Gives the directory where tla will create
	      its history files.  It must not exist prior to running
	      this command.
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	</varlistentry>

	<varlistentry><term>working_location</term>
	  <listitem><para>Gives the directory where you will work with
	      &dbp; on a daily basis.
	    </para>
	  </listitem>
	</varlistentry>
      </variablelist>
    </refsect1>
      
